Inflation in Europe has slipped to food.
The accelerated inflation, as measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the rise in prices in the 13 euro area countries was larger than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the statistical office of the European Community in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts showed only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate, saying that the decrease in interest rates, with the growth of commodity prices and the decrease in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to 2%.
One analyst says that this is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "we need to dissuade" inflation so that we do not have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is the highest in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has soared due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The cereal futures market shares rose by 88 per cent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil has risen by 52 percent, and last month a barrel of black gold was worth almost 100 dollars.
According to the ECB, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1% in 2008 to 2.5% this year, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup says there's a government crisis.
After a long period of stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December, and now it has the largest number of supporters since 2002, while Gallup (the polling institute) has never before recorded such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two thirds (71 per cent) against a support of a fifth (20 per cent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of the loyal voters who did go to the polls, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered that the economic situation of the country was particularly serious was never higher, it stands at 41 percent and according to 46 percent additional the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a worsening of the situation and only one tenth expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority unseen in previous Gallup polls, said the prime minister was doing his job poorly rather than well.
13 percent of the respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent the Fidesz president.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of the public who believe that the dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of those polled wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, at present this figure is only 20 per cent.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60% of respondents said they would certainly vote and an additional 20% said they would probably vote.
For comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 per cent of those polled would certainly participate and 15 per cent more would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to tuition fees for higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital fees.
If we look at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs shopping triangle have maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs shopping triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, with an increase of well over one thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already risen in large food stores last December, have not increased sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased for well under nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this amount was HUF 6800.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained at almost the same level as last year, but prices for turkey fillets, nuts and peacock have risen sharply.
In shops, the price of flour and bread followed the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) data, but at Auchan, bread was found for only 139 forints per kilo.
Competition did not bring the price of the product below HUF 200.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was under 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of the Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of her daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan have increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year's most expensive basket to this year's least expensive basket, we see a 12 percent gap whereas the difference between last year's cheapest basket and this year's most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of HUF 1,480 per person.
Last year prices increased by an average of HUF 1 206, although the impact of the VAT rate increase was already felt in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has left the trade perplexed, as hypermarkets were unable to clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adjusted to the intensity of trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the daily basket has changed so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1 720 HUF higher than the value of the one in 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 HUF.
This year the difference was not so great, as the most expensive basket was worth HUF 1 630 more than last year and the cheapest basket was worth HUF 1 284 more.
Bringing the two seasons of Christmas closer together, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foodstuffs, the statistical institute has found a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
The indices show that flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the multinationals to accept the sharp price increases.
In the commercial golden triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain, they consistently record good years.
In our experience, most customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets we visited.
They buy everything in bulk, they take long-stored food in pallets.
Large queues formed at the checkout desks of the three hypermarkets on Wednesday morning as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the provinces, many multinational companies complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for consumer durable goods.
Many hospitals are cutting back on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the misuse of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, insufficient beds, and overworked medical staff do not help to stop infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
Many hospitals are also cutting back on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a man who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
Earlier this year, a similar infection occurred in the same area.
The man who was injured in a serious car accident was released from the hospital but shortly afterwards he had to be returned due to an MRSA infection and since then the doctors have been unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his system.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Hospital Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
That is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing any disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used in excess or inappropriately, the bacteria, which respond well to antibiotics, will develop a highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital-acquired infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, underweight or weakened patients.
According to the chief physician of János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only there or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SA is resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Initially, patients in hospital are screened for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
Sampling is not the new trend
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not conducive to preventing the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is most prevalent in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and isolate patients with MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases are not diagnosed until the MRSA infection is detectable in the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict guidelines on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, in other words microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological testing is even more rare in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals are cutting back on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often spread from one patient to another through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, wear gloves and face masks, but there are significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area as well.
MRSA proliferates through infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and through contact. However, due to the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be separated from each other by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for the social security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has set up a programme to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections are showing a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) and the prevention of hospital-acquired infections caused by these pathogens.
The police commissioner, who caused a fatal accident, was not drunk.
The official report of the fatal accident caused by the 22nd precinct commissioner has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd district, resigned from his post since, who hit a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven drunk or dizzy, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Ministry of Public prosecution of the capital after the relevant finding was established.
The finding confirmed the initial outcome of the inquiry which had already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving
