Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without any commitment commission.
Bulgaria, the EU's housing market paradise
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this Balkan country that was little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will soon become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Bulgaria is currently the most popular real estate target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more people are looking for a property in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to analysts at Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and more and more of them are also buying in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, with the commercial and office space offering the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golfing paradises in Europe and thus to be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying real estate in Bulgaria are also looking to change their lives, their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English, but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and, increasingly, Romania.
The European Union has also been involved in the development of the European Union's policy on the environment, and in the implementation of the European Union's policy on the environment.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who are planning to move in buy newly renovated buildings, which cost between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old, dilapidated houses, which cost between 5 and 15 thousand euros, and are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and, in general, the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realising a capital gain in the medium to long term.
The price of buildings in the capital is rising steadily because of the increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but over the last five years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in house prices is essentially outstripping the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, but on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
There are now lively discussions on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that, for the moment, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, but that it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level.
Another important topic at the conference is whether developed countries commit, beyond emissions reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries that need it.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund set up under the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, presumably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for the Environment and Water, confirmed the EU's ambition to retain its role as flagship in the global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, irrespective of the success of the post-2012 agreement, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments appropriate to their responsibility and capabilities.
The Commission is also proposing that the EU should be able to take part in the negotiations on the future of the EU, and that the EU should be able to take part in the negotiations on the future of the EU.
Hungary has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level between 1985 and 1987, and our country will meet its commitment, the press release of the Ministry of the Environment recalls.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed beyond 2012. In that case, the commitments to reduce below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was underlined in the new report of the IPCC, the international scientific body, which won the Nobel Peace Prize from the UN, charged with dealing with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
The video sharing site is used by British Army units to share footage of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to gain popularity.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has taken to YouTube: Special Forces units in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and then they are transferred to London or uploaded by compatriots on the Internet.
The political message is essential
Air Force soldiers have already uploaded 139 videos to the net and their "channel" has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The UK Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and posts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Keeping Force in Iraq (IPFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the original purpose of the air force, the videos were posted online for recruitment purposes, and according to the Ministry of Defense, they were also used to inform the general public about the real purposes of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published by this channel costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defense consultant, told the BBC. However, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the justification of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have made a game
The army is embarrassed because, apart from carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been posted on the sharing site that also show, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never show the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted online showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real missions, but the British Army has only recently been busy uploading these videos.
The Americans do recruitment a little differently by using the free downloadable rifle game America's Army, in which the player can directly put themselves in the soldiers' shoes in a more or less real simulation.
