The forces of the mega strike are gathering
The League's unions and the National Association of Workers' Councils will set up their strike committee on Friday, which will be responsible for coordinating the indefinite strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and BKV employees will also strike until 1pm.
The League's unions will announce details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils, on Friday afternoon.
The strike committee of LIGA-MOSZ will also be formed, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, starting Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they cannot reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the health insurance law, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the agenda for Monday in the National Assembly, the vote on the health insurance bill is likely to take place late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, there are expected to be significant traffic jams: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half the track will also be blocked.
Many unions and civil society organisations have joined the call for a strike, and the list of these is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organisations report that they are on indefinite strike, others have declared a temporary work stoppage.
As of Thursday afternoon, the MÁV (Hong Kong Railways) and the Free Railway Workers' Union (VDSZSZ) had not been able to reach an agreement on minimum services, and as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to the current communications, the public transport in Budapest will strike from the beginning of service until 1 pm, the Budapest airport between 7 and 9 am, the Electricity and Thermal Energy Industrial Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union called for a strike for 2 hours and 2 hours to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Doctors will strike nationwide in alternating shifts, the Health and Social Workers' Union (EDDSZ) affiliated to the SZEF will strike for two hours.
The most important of the four demands put forward by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of pension calculation to be introduced from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third demand is for a guarantee of early retirement, which would allow the system to be filled with the functions it deserves before 2010.
The fourth ground of appeal is the rejection by the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), which is affiliated to the League of Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economic Affairs and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to Political Capital's Risk Analysis Division, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was formed last August with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
In its  risk warning , the company notes that the biggest political risk in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity is already that  in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur as a result of the worsening of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary .
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy to bring about this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors:  the public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma issue to the representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and the Hungarians .
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue is made impossible, extremists are empowered and aggressive conflict is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media to the activity of the Hungarian Guard  has significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially regarding confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity .
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been established in Hungary since summer 2007 calling themselves the National Self-Defense Association.
 The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civil organization while publicly declaring the readiness of their members for defense missions (disasters, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, moreover, by evoking the inadequacy of the police, the army, in other words the state , they added.
They reported that everything was done according to the method which, based on the resentment of society of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil character and association status thus not only serves to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering such associations in court but also constitutes a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighbourly relations.
 In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries have sought to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the Hungarian Guard constitution.
This is affecting the political stability of the region, they added.
According to the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, political risks have increased across the region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard resembles, for example, the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The numerous Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) led to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard.
