The party's not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines the exact dates of public holidays and it has become common practice to reorganise working days around the holidays, the number of which will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform across the EU and the US as well.
The Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and rest days.
Holidays are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year is also a day of rest, the latter especially so that the awakeners can rest quietly.
In addition, in a year, we have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 which is the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
August 20th is our state's founding day, May 1st is Labor Day, and November 1st and 2nd are our memorial days for family and friends who have passed away.
Besides, we have two days in Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since the days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, it has become common practice to re-arrange the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has laid down special rules for the replacement of days before or after holidays.
The law extends to all employers and to all their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service societies, institutions which are in continuous operation and in service by virtue of their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24 onwards, life almost stops in the whole country because according to experiments the majority of people rather work overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes in order to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in the working days compared to this year.
The schedule will be reorganized the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay home for four days straight.
Saturday, April 25th will be a working day, with a rest day on Friday, May 2nd.
Another change is planned for 23 October: Saturday, 18 October, will be a working day, replacing Friday, 24 October.
However, next year, the end of the year is coming under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
