Before you give any unpleasant explanations, it is helpful to think about how you might cause unpleasant situations to your coworkers and to make efforts to avoid them.
You borrow something that doesn't belong to you?
There's nothing more annoying than wanting to pick up a file, a desk tool or your phone and it's nowhere to be found.
Do you remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it was gone the next morning?
You find your pen you thought was missing on your co-worker's desk?
Don't take anything from your coworkers without asking, or they'll be rightly angry at you for stealing their property.
Don't bring envelopes, post-its in your pocket because it can be annoying that there are no more and you need it right away.
You're talking about the private lives of your coworkers?
There are no good ways to stop gossip from spreading.
Who did what with who?
Or why?
Do not share your (supposed) information about the privacy of your colleagues!
If a fellow worker shares intimate secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Bury the information you've shared and don't discuss it with your co-workers in his absence even if your co-workers know about it too.
You call in sick for no good reason?
When you call the office and you call in sick under the pretext of a tearing headache because you feel sick or you feel you need to rest that day, remember that your work, your urgent business, your missions in the future must be done by someone else instead of you.
Don't bother your coworkers!
If you know in advance that you will not be at work the next day or that something may happen that will require you to stay at home, be sure to let your boss and your coworkers know so that they will not be surprised that you will be absent the next day.
Flirting, laughing, and calling
You're immersed in your work, but the nagging of your colleagues suddenly pulls you away?
Have you unintentionally become an eyewitness to a telephone conversation that you should have ignored?
Do not disturb your co-workers by humming, singing, loudly arguing (leading over their heads), kicking, cursing or loudly complaining.
They can be annoying even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, designing, organising).
You blame others for a mistake?
If you miss a deadline, or if you forget to send an important message or e-mail, do not blame yourself!
Don't blame it on the chaos in the office or on your noisy coworkers!
If you have done wrong, admit it, and if it has caused harm to others, make amends.
Ask how you can make amends for your mistake, make up for your negligence!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Wearing a jogging boot and shoes is comfortable at home but not in the office!
Don't wear a comfortable jogging suit even if your function allows it!
Don't be sloppy, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your job requires it by wearing nice and stylish clothes, to go to work.
