Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of England, Switzerland and Canada have agreed to fight the crisis in the financial markets together.
More than $100 billion will be placed on the money markets through auctions.
This will be for the banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will auction off $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual countries have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even lessen the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing shortage of free capital that banks could lend", wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"The concerted action of central banks has reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 per cent to about 50 per cent", Baumohl adds in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts are expecting billions more in losses.
"If central banks have chosen this approach, they must really understand what may follow", says ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", he added.
The central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficulty in accessing loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the US economy into a recession that could affect economic growth worldwide.
Central banks made this choice after the failure to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still apprehensive about mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the US, Canadian and British central banks had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as a further decline in interest rates", said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
