The integration of Slovak pupils into British schools is going badly
The number of children from Eastern Europe in British schools is increasing, causing concern amongst the residents about the evolution of local education.
The integration of Eastern Europeans is currently facing a number of obstacles.
British schools have even seen cases where conflicts between immigrants and descendants of the original inhabitants have turned violent.
The case of northern Kent, where conflicts between immigrants of Slovak origin and immigrants of Slovak origin are becoming more acute, illustrates the problem of the integration of children from Eastern Europe.
The quarrels, the squabbles and the fights between the pupils have been transferred to the relations between the parents.
The situation went so far that the police in Chatham arrested a Slovak woman who was beating a ten-year-old student with an iron bar.
The accused defends himself by claiming that the boy insulted him with racist remarks.
Police also had to intervene following the attack on a Slovakian immigrant by two teenage girls.
The girls allegedly made racist remarks and threw stones at the man.
"On the way home, a young man climbed onto the bus stop and began spitting at us.
When I told him to stop, he responded with apples and pears and then he uncovered his buttocks", another unpleasant experience was described by a mother of Slovak schoolchildren.
Complaints are made by both parties.
One of the Remainers went so far as to describe the conflicts with the immigrants as a struggle for survival.
The cases mentioned above show that the atmosphere in British schools between the native inhabitants and the immigrants is beginning to become tense.
70 000 Slovaks who came to find work are registered in Britain.
And about 30,000 Slovak students are in British schools.
Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it truly is an island of freedom.
Whatever you want from your vacation, it can be if you make the right choice.
Gold and white beaches like snow, high waves or calm sea like a pond.
Palm trees and all-inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach pizza, ice cream or even intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will find this list not only in its entirety, but enriched.
But there is only one island where you will find much more, and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island of the Greater Antilles.
In the days of the Spanish, Cuba had been the stronghold of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the depot and transshipment point for the treasures that the Spanish had stolen and carried to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920's.
Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, had it built, since everything that was a crime in the USA (especially under prohibition) was allowed and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
I mean, Winston Churchill, and Ava Gardner, and Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, tall buildings have sprung up and cars, the cult symbols of the 1950s, have flown along the wide boulevards.
Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
The stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can even sign your own autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be served the cocktail of your choice.
And those cult cars are still running in Havana, because the jigoulis and the fiats that were imported have long since, in such a salty and humid climate, rotted.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is markedly outlined, nowhere else in the vicinity are there so many splendid colonial monuments as there are there.
Other places are getting more beautiful, like Trinidad.
Since tourism brings in money when needed, its development is given the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana but especially in Varader, on the coast of Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba also offers a unique fantasy that will be appreciated by lovers of small trains.
The cane was brought back from the extensive plantations into the sugar mills on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been updated for decades, and so small locomotives can be seen in operation, the contemporaries of which are only in museums.
Where to go?
Most visitors do not miss the most famous places.
So there is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
And, of course, the Hemingway estate, mentioned earlier, is a museum that is a must-visit for any fan of the author.
The Viňales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque parts of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows on the calcareous soil.
From the bottom of the valley, the ground is covered with mosses, limestone balloons, and rocks, and the fertile earth has taken hold of their entrails, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetation.
The valley is probably the best place to grow Cuban tobacco.
You can see the final shape of this product by visiting one of the cigar factories in Havana.
One might also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was filmed.
The Republic of Trinidad
Ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought him fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beauty and the showcase character of this small town.
The colonial Spanish architecture, strongly influenced by later French settlers, has remained almost unchanged for four centuries.
Trinidad, situated between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is so remote that even in the 1950s there was no road linking the region to the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay out of the way.
They didn't build anything, and that's why they didn't demolish anything either, they just had a roof over their heads.
If you have more than an afternoon in Trinidad, then it is worth visiting some of the interesting places in the surrounding area, such as Playa Ancón or Sucre Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música, which comes to life after sunset and where the music is only heard in the early morning.
The Barcoas
Some call this town in the far east of Cuba the most beautiful town on the island.
This view is certainly already influenced by the path that leads to it.
The two routes from Guantánamo to the island must cross high, rugged mountains and a landscape with almost no trace of human activity.
The UNESCO has included the Eastern Cove of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, in the list of World Heritage Sites.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (actually, it came into existence about a hundred years after Columbus's voyage) and from the hill where the old castle and the current El Castillo hotel stand, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
Coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain range, the Bay of Pigs and Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the shrine of Cuba's patron saint Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, the African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves - all of these things could fill a whole book.
But, as they say, it's better to see once.
In Afghanistan, the allies are passive, says the Americans
The lack of soldiers and equipment is affecting the conduct of the mission in Afghanistan, according to the United States.
According to Defense Secretary Robert Gates, NATO should draw up a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland, by representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to the growing opposition of the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are now also discussing future plans and coordination of alliances.
While the United States this week through Defense Secretary Robert Gates called for NATO troops to be more active, Britain sees as a priority the strengthening of the authority of the Afghan government and the intensification of development aid.
"The situation in Afghanistan is changing, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the people to start a new development of the economy and security themselves", British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent of the
Afghan insurgent activity is, according to US military data, the most intense in the last five years.
Violent acts have increased by 27 percent compared to last year, up to 60 percent in the southern province of Helmand.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern part.
But according to the United States, the Allies have reached their absolute limit in both organization and equipment of troops.
In concrete terms, they are asking for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about the concrete objectives for the period ahead, as well as the ways in which we can achieve them", said Gates.
The NATO Secretary-General, Jaap de Hoop, made similar comments today.
"I'm not happy with what we have on the ground and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the troops and equipment we would need, and that is not enough", De Hoop told Reuters at the end of three days of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
In recent months there have also been conflicts between the countries concerned over whether all the allies are really doing their best in Afghanistan.
Germany, for example, has been criticized for its passivity.
"Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where the violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as rigorous as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate", Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun this week called German soldiers lazy.
"Afghan idlers uncovered: the Germans play, while ours fight", Sun wrote in a document complete with pictures of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild has taken the counter-attack by publishing a photo of a British squad at a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
The national debt will rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a public debt of over 84,000 crowns lies on every Czech.
The total debt at the end of September was 842.7 billion.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
The Ministry reduced the amount planned to 152.8 billion kroner, as the state budget was more economical than expected.
The Czech Republic's public debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
In the nine months of this year it has therefore increased by 40.2 billion.
However, from June onwards, it fell by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the state debt as of the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt of over 84,000 crowns is on each Czech.
During the whole of last year, the state incurred over 111 billion crowns in debt.
"For the time being, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could exceed the one trillion crown limit in 2009 alone.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and 1 trillion crowns", Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor has similar forecasts: "We could exceed a trillion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget, which is not yet known.
If it appears that the political situation is changing, that politicians are ready to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I don't expect that change", he said.
Debts are rising
The national debt is the central government's debt and is essentially generated by the accumulation of deficits in the national budget.
The public debt is financed by treasury bonds, interest-rate securities, direct borrowings or, for example, by borrowings from the European Investment Bank.
The national debt has increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The external debt of the state has increased this year by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion crowns.
The negotiable government debt reached SEK 803.3 billion at the end of September and has decreased by SEK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the public debt was 6.5 years.
"The total debt has increased by 13 per cent year on year from the first to the third half of the year, which is, given the current good health of the economy, far too high a figure.
Interestingly, the increase was mainly driven by pension securities, where it reached 20 per cent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be negotiating material when the pension reform comes", commented Pikora data.
Better than we expected
It follows from the strategy for financing and managing the state debt for the year 2007 that the government planned to borrow 159,2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of September, the Ministry reduced the amount planned to 152.8 billion kroner, thanks to better than expected savings in the State budget.
The sum is essentially the deficit of the state budget which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns originally planned.
Secondly, there are the maximum resources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, i.e. CZK 13,3 billion, the reserve of CZK 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state pension securities for CZK 43 billion and the repayment of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to CZK 1,8 billion.
She appeared in court today in Khartoum for naming a teddy bear after a man she had been with for years.
The British teacher on trial in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced on Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in jail and deportation, her lawyer said.
The Briton was accused of having let pupils aged 6 to 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear when any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was liable to be whipped.
The 54-year-old British teacher, who works at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with insulting Islam and sedition under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually dates back to September, when the teacher asked her students, who were six or seven years old, to choose a name for the class's teddy bear.
"Eight names are coming out of the mouths of the children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed", said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 of the 23 children chose Mohamed as their favorite name.
Mohammed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but it's especially a very common first name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the picture of the bear followed by the caption "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not carry any label with that name, but the problem is simply that the depiction of the prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name", and that it was just an "innocent mistake".
Many of her students shared her opinion, describing her as "very attentive to her students" and "never talking about religion in class".
The name Mohamed is also the second most common given name in Britain, spelled in 14 different ways.
This name is often chosen by Muslim families as a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules for using that first name?
Can we give it to a toy, for example?
This is of course a matter of interpretation.
They failed to reach an agreement on the future status of the province on Wednesday, at the last round of negotiations in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
The Serbs and Albanians of Kosovo concluded a sixth and final session of talks in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without overcoming their differences over the future status of the breakaway province.
It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status, said European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger, at a press conference in Vienna.
Underlining that peace in the region was at stake, his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to honour their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
'There is no immediate violence planned but we are entering a very difficult period' he added, noting that 'clear tensions exist'.
End of mediation on 10 December
The troika of mediators from the European Union, the United States and Russia will make their final visits to Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is 90% Albanian-speaking, could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and last round of negotiations since the troika was given a new UN mediation mandate last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on continuing the negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution", said Botsane-Khartchenko.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, the West believes that independence under EU supervision is the only viable solution.
Pristina said she was ready to unilaterally proclaim it if the Security Council did not decide in her favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
'Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached,' announced the president of the Autonomous Authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the Baden hotel where the 'last chance' negotiations were taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future premier of the province, expressed his regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations".
Domino effect
The Serbian President Boris Tadic said that a compromise was still possible, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence for the province.
Belgrade said it feared a 'domino effect' in a region still weakened by the wars of independence in the 1990s.
'For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.'
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision rests solely with the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto.
The Parliament of Kosovo will have the final say
'Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia', declared the Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
The negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: at the Security Council.
Fatmir Sedjiu told reporters that "the Parliament of Kosovo will have the final say on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking people would be "in consultation" with the Westerners.
Bush pulls an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
President Bush announced at the opening of the international peace conference he was chairing in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday that the Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately to find a final settlement to the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised to do everything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must dismantle "terrorist infrastructure" and Israel must end its settlement activities, said Bush, reminding both sides of their obligations under the "road map" for peace they agreed to in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas's chairmanship would aim "to conclude a peace treaty resolving all outstanding issues, without exception, including the core issues".
This appellation covers the three thorny issues at the heart of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees driven from their homes in what is now the State of Israel during the 1948 conflict.
Speaking after the US president, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be "global and in-depth" and cover all aspects of a settlement, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among others".
Speaking in turn, Olmert pledged that the talks would be "direct and continuous" and "an effort to conclude them in the course of 2008".
Bush set a deadline of the end of 2008 for the implementation of his "two-state vision" of Palestinian and Israeli coexistence.
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had obtained a commitment to this from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
Saudi Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a success for Washington, is behind a plan, endorsed by all Arab countries, that offers Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks "a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, particularly because it tackles the roots of the conflict and its central aspects", said Prince Saud in his interview with the Saudi-owned Arabic-language daily.
