A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives in Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were previously only available for consultation for humanitarian purposes, i.e. individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or his heirs.
The 11 states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The ratification process of this agreement by all the States having been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for research including on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced labourers, explains Reto Meistern, the director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some of the deportation victims.
The records of concentration camps and Gestapo arrest warrants were collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, so as to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
 There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents, said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
