The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine is a wake-up call.
A dispute over gas prices is raging between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of a spillover on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are transported by pipeline, and each pipeline is closely monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia raises the cost of fuel, it will increase transit fees to Russia.
Last year, a clash between the two caused a drop in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia's gas monopoly, tried in vain to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine in 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as planned, given that it agreed to pay for 2008 up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said that this would result in Ukraine having to pay 40% more for imports from Gazprom.
 It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the talks, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas is transiting,  Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters news agency.
 The fluctuations in gas costs are probably related to our discussions about transit fees (to Western Europe) via Ukraine 
The last major altercation between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 caused the interruption of Gazprom's supplies to Ukraine.
This has led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, and consequently to higher prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's gas supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves, although most of them are still undeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Union nations in Central Asia.
