The climate of Venus could reveal the future of Earth.
Scientists yesterday declared that Venus was certainly a habitable planet.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are practically the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to Earth's, and may even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect from carbon dioxide, the erosion of the atmosphere from solar radiation, combined with a slower rotation, has led Venus into a whole different kind of evolution.
Today the planet is without water, ravaged by hurricanes and thunderstorms, and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a bleak picture of Earth's potential future due to catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the University of Oxford's physics department, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: 'We are beginning to understand why the climate of Venus is so different from that of Earth, although the planets themselves are practically similar.
Our new data allows us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to Earth, perhaps even with a habitable surface.
