The pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has found a new hole to sink into; even if he resigned, the situation would not change.
Given the pattern of British scandals, this one is not particularly juicy.
No sold decorations, no bills from the Paris hotels of politicians, no extra-marital toes sucked.
But now a revelation that a wealthy businessman had hidden his contributions to the current Labour Party, worth over £650,000 ($1.3m), under false names for four years, which the party would not have declared: a new battle that Gordon Brown would have been fine without.
Two months ago, the Prime Minister backtracked on his election plan, foolishly insulting British intelligence by proclaiming that the opinion polls had not influenced his decision, and that he hoped instead to deliver a compact and effective government.
On the contrary, as Vince Cable, the brilliant liberal Democrat leader, has said, the terrifying Mr. Brown has transformed himself from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The takeover of Northern Rock, a struggling bank on the brink of crack, demonstrated a flaw in the guidelines and poor judgment in an emergency.
The inadequate proposals for changes to the tax code have provoked a coalition of industrial groups against the government.
The loss of 25 million personal data by the tax authorities has revealed an incredible administrative blunder.
A trio of retired generals have launched a revolt among the Lords, protesting against cuts to military spending: they have proclaimed that being Minister of Defence is for them, a part-time job.
At present, suspicion of suspicious donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and his former vigilante chief) have forced him to resign.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is headed for the exit.
Yet governments can reach a point where it would be impossible to govern.
People don't like politicians, and they don't trust them, but they usually put their doubts aside when a new government comes into power.
It seems clear that a prime minister cannot make things better, or even govern for long, when he is at risk of suspension: the public administration is out of order; cabinets of ministers are being checked; the press is looking for bad stories; and the government is on the defensive and has no purpose.
In a sense, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders, he cannot boast of being a beginner.
Although he would like to remove Tony Blair, he was still his senior lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and with tax data, for example, are related to decisions taken by Mr Brown when he was Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he is not directly involved in Blair's misfortunes, such as the lengthy investigation into party funds - the cash for members of the House of Lords - voters might think otherwise.
But Mr. Brown's predicament is not as tragic as it may seem.
The blunders are not as monstrous as the Tory Party members make them out to be.
Like Mr. Bean, there are no victims and no scam.
And the remedy, however painful, might be to materialize Mr. Brown's old Stalinist tendencies in favor of a reliable and slightly brutal government.
The new political donation scandal is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, a very particular character, who compares his donations to charity, said he did not want any public recognition of his charity.
He may have an opinion, but it's not his call.
Laws against the anonymity of politicians' big donors are clear, and they exist for a good reason: The public has a right to know who contributes to the success of those who will govern the country.
Mr. Watt, who claimed to be aware of Mr. Abrahams's programs, without knowing that it was illegal, will therefore be questioned, as will, incidentally, Jon Mendlesohn, the fundraising manager who spoke of questionable donations in October.
But so far Mr Brown is not involved: there is no indication that he was aware of these proceedings, even though most of the payments made were made as a result of his arrival in government in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half.
He was quick to condemn his party's legislative loophole, but he failed to draw attention to the fact that the decision-making power rests on something he knows well, the use of a committee of inquiry on this subject composed of a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons to be learned are not complicated.
And if the law was broken, it's the police's job.
In addition, there are many other things Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been without a leader for six months, and preparing a good reform on the financing of political parties.
It would force the Labour Party, in a moment of weakness, to collaborate with the Tories, which might lead to it giving up its particular financial relationship with the confederations; in short, a bitter pill for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he'll have to face some partisan facts.
The Conservative Party now has a good lead in the election; it has two years to win back the electorate, and the only way to secure a victory is to demonstrate impeccable integrity and sound skills.
Card and card fraud.
Would the mortgage crisis contaminate the U.S. credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's normal to see some flapping fins, swirling around.
Now that the U.S. housing market is in crisis, predators are targeting the U.S. credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs believe that credit-card losses could reach $99 billion if the contagion spreads from mortgages to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are rises in the expense and insolvency rates, which measure the shares of the balance sheet that are not recoverable or are recoverable, more than 30 days after.
HSBC announced last month that it took $1.4 billion in consumer credit, in part because of weak cardholders.
It's too soon to panic.
The costs and insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody's, a tax agency, the third quarter insolvency rate of 3.89% is almost one point below its historical average.
The deterioration in rates is partly explained by technical factors.
A change in the laws in 2005 in the United States regarding personal bankruptcy caused a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn caused heavy losses for credit cards; the number of filings (and thus insolvency rates) could increase even if borrowing conditions were to worsen.
The industry also advertises fixed payment rates, which highlight the amount of monthly debt that consumers have to pay.
And confidence in the safety of credit card capital is quite strong despite the paralysis of other aspects of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicted that the 2007 emission volume will be 25% higher than last year.
Direct contagion links between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers may prefer to increase their debt now that equitable home loans have disappeared.
But card issuers are more concerned with cash flow than asset value, and so the fall in house prices has not necessarily led to a change in the creditworthiness of borrowers.
They may even provide advantages to credit issuers.
Consumer premiums for mortgage payments fall if properties cost less than the value of the loan; therefore, credit card debt would become a priority to pay it all back.
Card issuers are able to respond much more quickly and with more flexibility than mortgage companies to such crisis conditions, as they can change interest rates or alter credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid stock recovery.
"We're not going to wake up one morning and re-evaluate every loan", said Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief executive.
If a financial disaster in the credit card market is unlikely, there are strong chances of a significant decline.
If lower housing prices and a contraction in the credit market is driving America into recession, the industry will certainly face a macabre future.
Watch the dorsal fins carefully.
British bankers plead guilty in the Enron case.
The three British bankers who were due to testify about their roles in a fraud committed by Enron's former chief financial officer, Mr Andrew Fastow, changed their plea to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had initially pleaded not guilty to seven counts of alleged collusive fraud in 2000, committed by Fastow in a secret financial scam to enrich himself at the expense of their employees.
They should be in court in January.
But during a hearing presided over by U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., they all pleaded guilty to committing fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland PLC group, have become famous throughout Britain because of the two-year extradition proceedings.
In the United States, their case remains an open point in this investigation launched after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges against them in 2002 made Fastow aware that he was the subject of the government's investigation into the Enron debacle.
The charges against the bankers, dubbed the "Natwest Three", allege they came to Houston in 2000 to set up a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the mastermind of many fraudulent scenarios, which helped him rig the bankruptcy proceedings.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the subsidiary as zero, but in fact the three British already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank's interest in the subsidiary for £1 million.
The bankers paid $250,000 to Kopper as interest on this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely told Enron that the energy company was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But the truth is that $20 million went into the pockets of the British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the indictment, the bankers were awarded $7.3 million while Fastow, Kopper and others were awarded $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty for his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving three years and one month in a Texas prison.
The three British men were released on $1 million bail each, which obliged them to live in the United States during the trial.
Enron, once the seventh largest company in the nation, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, and could no longer hide its billions in debt or even offer its phony speculations as profitable.
The collapse caused thousands of job cuts, more than $60 billion in lost market value and more than $2 billion in lost pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their involvement in the company's collapse.
Skilling was sentenced to over 24 years in prison.
Charges against Lay for conspiracy, fraud and other offenses were dropped due to his death from a heart attack last year.
