Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought: the European space probe Venus Express has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirls at the poles, similar to those seen on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have speculated that there are lightning bolts on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now provided evidence of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus erupts from cloud to cloud at a height of about 35 miles [56 km], reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprinid theory, lightning bolts would have brought life to Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life existed there, it must have been at a very early date in history", says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little life on the surface of Venus today. The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures can reach 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but she's still a twin", Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, was hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the Venusian search, as no other probe had been on its way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results which have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" do not only underline the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that our neighboring planet Earth has more in common with it than was originally thought.
So, in addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, the researchers found a whirlwind of clouds at the South Pole that rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system is almost as massive as the Earth and is almost as large, with a diameter of 7,500 miles.
The planet, called the evening or morning star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, its rotation is much slower: a day on Venus lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists speculate that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost to space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
