These aren't Warhols boxes.
The one that links the concepts of Sweden and wooden crate, Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast a shadow on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxes listed there are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a dismal conclusion: the six Brillo-Boxes, which the former museum director Pontus Hulten gave to Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - along with many of the hundreds of other Brillo-Boxes of the "Type Stockholm" that circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is a tangle, a bewildering succession of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - featured hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come from Warhol (for financial reasons), but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather models of them, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes which at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions as original Brillo-Boxes by Andy Warhol, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached auction sales of over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum later claimed, wrongly, that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later have given to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén cases were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, besides the six Brillo-Boxes in the museum, three others from Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, shows that the paint was applied directly without a backing layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - and it is not an oil paint but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes", suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material".
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious allegations" that were raised in the soap-powder case.
But since then, we've been living in an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers are giving up, the same ones who had holed up in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who has accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not be held responsible for any bloodshed.
The hotel had been stormed by soldiers loyal to the government with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them were in court on Wednesday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly disappear with about 30 supporters.
The military police, who were normally supposed to keep an eye on them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined the mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The troops loyal to the government have sealed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President called an emergency meeting of the Security Council.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the action of the soldiers.
"People have had enough", said Trillanes.
"We are calling for people to join us".
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite Scout Ranger unit, said other units in the army wanted to join the march soon.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded by accusations of corruption for months.
The financial district of Manila was already the scene of the 2003 mutiny attempt by about 200 members of the military against Arroyo.
The insurrection broke out almost 24 hours after the refusal of the army to join it.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes a major shareholder in Versatel.
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday.
Only 20.05% of the share capital would be held.
We've speculated about a buyout before.
The option to increase the shareholding in Versatel further would remain open.
The move is aimed at accelerating the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Just before that, speculation had already been made on Wednesday about a takeover, after Berenberg Bank had increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator from 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The credit institution would hold only one-third of the money, the market says.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a stake of nearly 10% in the mobile telephone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch put on the stock exchange 17,4 million new shares worth EUR 106,4 million.
United Internet bought 5.15 million of them for 31.1 million euros.
In addition, the companies have entered into negotiations on cooperation in the marketing of DSL and mobile telephony products.
"We are strengthening our partnership", said a United Internet spokesman.
The two companies set up the joint venture MSP to take over the competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to consider themselves satisfied with their ten percent stake in Freenet, and not to exercise their right to buy an additional 18.49 percent stake in Freenet, United Internet said on Thursday.
The two companies would, however, leave all options open, especially to increase participation in the Freenet SA, it was learned.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership were concluded in mid-October.
The still unpredictable poker on Freenet which has been going on for months is part of the consolidation of the German telecoms market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million customers with a mobile telephone contract and 1.27 million DSL and full subscription customers.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch held a direct stake in Freenet of 6.01% until now.
It has now been agreed that Drillisch would contribute about four per cent more.
The right to buy the 18.49% of the investment company Vatas had already been decided in August.
